Transport | Where We Stand Post 2Q25 Results

Earnings were resilient in a volatile environment & the forwarders demonstrated organic growth continues, even with tariffs. We prefer DSV over KNIN with Cons incorporating c6% org growth & no upside to synergies (Figure 2). Our top pick is DHL. 2Q Express margins were +140bps (+190bps ex cost of change) even with B2C volumes - 20%/US volumes - 31% (Figure 1). We expect the headwind from de minimus to be much lower than the max c€200m highlighted on the call.

Where We Stand Post Reporting. In the forwarders, we prefer DSV over KNIN. Valuations are aligned by 1H28, but DSV offers stronger, synergy- driven earnings growth through '29. We also see upside to Cons for DSV, with sets incorporating no upside to synergies & c6- 7% organic growth. DHL remains our top pick with management showing that they can grow earnings even in weak volume environments (eg 2Q). With fiscal stimulus & easing monetary policy in Europe yet to hit the road, DHL's large regional exposure to Europe should turn into a tailwind by 2026.

De minimus, the post & integrated freight. De minimus shipments grew to \(1.4bn\) in '24 with the majority arriving by air (c80%), followed by truck (c13%) & with c60% of these shipments arriving from China. Of the c1.1bn that arrive by air, c190m are express & c75m by post. In 2Q, DHL B2C Express volumes were - 20% with total US Express volumes - 31%. The data points indicate Express 'de minimus' volumes into the US were already down c50- 60%. With a resilient EBIT performance in Express in 2Q, despite the large volume decline, & given the potential for some switching from post to Express (postal services are refusing packages), we see the worst- case €200m impact as highly unlikely.

- DHL earnings guidance for '26 was unchanged, with the group EBIT expected to exceed €6bn ex a max €200mn downside from changes to US de minimis laws. We don't think a much lower headwind than the max €200mn impact is likely.- Kuehne & Nagel lowered guidance for the year by 5% to account for a 5% drag from currency translation. The new range for EBIT guidance is CHF 1.45–1.65 bn (from 1.5-1.75bn).- DSV reiterated '25 EBIT guidance for DKK19.5-21.5b. Management believes that if conditions stay stable, it's hard to see a scenario where EBIT lands at the bottom end of the range.

DHL should benefit from a positive air freight outlook in FY25- 27, driven by the Red Sea reopening and supply constraints. With c. \(50\%\) market share, DHL is well- positioned to capitalise on these trends. High levels of investment from '18- '23 in their Express business have led to underutilization. However, with asset growth slowing in '25, we expect strong positive operating leverage as utilization improves. Supportive policy settings in Europe and potential demand recovery suggest a brighter outlook. Our SOTP & relative valuation reflects a premium multiple for DHL Express of 6.8x, given its positive market structure and leading position. On a relative basis, weaker cash generation justifies a discount to peers.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View
Our base case assumes peer multiples and a c20% discount to the fundamental SOTP for the various segments.
We assume: 13x EV/EBIT for Express, 12x EV/EBIT for P&P and eCommerce, 16x EV/EBIT for Forwarding, 18x EV/EBIT for Supply Chain
Upside Scenario, 81, +107%
Our upside scenario incorporates no holding discount to our fundamental SOTP.
Downside Scenario, 30, - 23%
Our downside scenario incorporates a \(60\%\) holding discount to our fundamental SOTP.

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Greenhouse gas emissions. All modes of freight contribute significantly to global CO2 emissions. We monitor the penetration of renewable energy to address exhaust emissions and companies plans to manage Scope 1 and Scope 2 emissions in freight. SAF mandate requires a minimum percentage of aviation fuel to be SAF, which is a low- carbon alternative to conventional jet fuel. 2) Energy management. This will be a growing focus for freight operators. We are monitoring progress in total energy consumption and the share of renewable energy.

Company Target(s): 1) net- zero emissions by 2050. 2) >30% share of sustainable fuels in Air and Sea by 2030.3) Increase sustainable fuels and electrification share in Road division to >30% by 2030.4) All new owned buildings to be carbon- neutral.

DSV delivers market leading margins, strong returns (ROIC), and will generate significant free cash flow in FY25- 27 which will see the balance sheet de- lever quickly.
With the acquisition of Schenker for EUR 14.3 bn, DSV will become the world's largest freight forwarder, with a market share of c.7%.

Scale remains the key competitive advantage, offering significant operational & commercial benefits. Based on the earlier successful integrations of UTi and Panalpina, we are confident DSV can create substantial shareholder value through Schenker.

Kuehne+Nagel is currently the world's second- largest freight forwarder, behind DHL, but will become third after the DSV Schenker acquisition. We are not pricing in improvements in current conversion ratios or EBIT margins.

K+N delivered a \(14\%\) EBIT CAGR between '18 and '23, primarily through organic growth with limited acquisitions. This was however, with peak freight conditions in '23. We expect organic growth to continue, however, capital allocation is the differentiator in the sector.
We have a Hold rating on Kuehne+Nagel, with a multiples based PT of CHF 240, valuing the company at 18.7x FY25E EV/EBIT.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View
We forecast revenues of CHF28bn and an adjusted EBIT margin of \(5.6\%\) in 2025.
We arrive at a CHF180 PT based on an EV/EBIT multiple of 15.4x FY25.

Our upside scenario arrives at a fair value of CHF 234 per share. In our upside case we apply the same EV/EBIT multiple, however, we assume that mgmt are successful in extracting 100bps additional EBIT margin over time.

Our downside scenario arrives at a fair value of CHF 144 per share. In our downside case we apply the same EV/EBIT multiple, however, we assume that costs accelerate at a faster pace than gross profit with margins deteriorating by 100bps over time.

SAF mandate requires require a minimum percentage of aviation fuel to be SAF, which is a low- carbon alternative to conventional jet fuel. 2) Energy management. This will be a growing focus for freight operators. We are monitoring progress in total energy consumption and the share of renewable energy.

Company Target(s): 1) Net zero by 2050 and develop tangible solutions to reduce GHG emissions in our value chain. 2) Reduce CO2 emissions by \(33\%\) for our, our suppliers' and customers' footprint by end 2030 (including Scope 3 of GHG Protocol).

DHL Group, operating through DHL and Deutsche Post, is a global leading logistics company active in the postal and parcel delivery areas, with service portfolio including mail and parcel, express, freight transport, supply chain management and e- commerce logistics solutions. Founded in 1969 and headquartered in Bonn, Germany, the consolidated revenues in 2023 were €81.8 bn.

DSV is one of the global leading freight forwarders operating through Air & Sea, Road Logistics, as well as Solutions. Founded in 1976 and headquartered in Hedelhusene, Denmark, the consolidated revenues in 2023 were DKK 150.8 bn.

Kuehne + Nagel is a global leading logistics company operating through Sea, Air and Road Logistics, as well as Contract Logistics. Founded in 1890 in Bremen, Germany and now headquartered in Schindellegi, Switzerland, the consolidated revenues in 2023 were CHF 26.6 bn.

Our multiple- based EUR 60 PT equates to 2025E EV/EBIT of 14.4x. Risks include worse- than- expected macro environment, weaker consumer demand, new mobility investments, losing market share, ramp- up issues in supply chain, operating leverage worse than expected, and FX. Risk factors include macroeconomic risks, related to COVID- 19, impacting freight markets, rate volatility, the ability to maintain competitive IT systems, acquisition integration risk and increasing competition from suppliers moving up the value chain.

DKK1700 PT based on an EV/EBIT multiple of 17.5x FY26 on a PF basis. Risk factors include macroeconomic risks, related to Covid- 19, impacting freight markets, rate volatility, the ability to maintain competitive IT systems, acquisition integration risk and increasing competition from suppliers moving up the value chain.

EV/EBIT based CHF 180.0 price target, assuming volume growth ahead of market growth. At price target, Kuehne + Nagel would trade at 15.4x FY25 EV/EBIT. Risk factors include macro- economic risks, related to Covid- 19, impacting freight markets, rate volatility, failure to keep IT systems up- to- date and increasingly complex regulation.
